Calibration Results Analysis

Marcos J Ribeiro

2025-05-15

1 Introduction

In this document, I analyze the calibration results. I calibrated the TFP using the sectoral gross output relative to the sectoral average gross output from the US, from data and model. For the model, I used the results of gross output from previous calibration that I did to US. The objective function that I proposed is:

\[Obj = \sum_i^N \left( \frac{ WGO_i^M - WGO_i^D }{WGO_i^D} \right)^2\] Where

\(WGO_i^D = GO_i^D/ \bar{GO}_{US}^D\)

\(WGO_i^M = GO_i^M/ \bar{GO}_{US}^M\)

The superscripts M and D means model and data, respectively.

The main advantages of this approach are:

  • It is easy to calibrate

  • The objective function converges to zero in almost all countries

  • It is easy to explain

  • The results make economic sense

  • The correlation between labor shares from data and the model is 90%

Observations:

  • I used a dataset 2014.

  • The GDP per person employed tnat I used here is from World Bank.

  • I didn’t use L=1, instead I used labor (from SEA) per hundred million inhabitants. This makes more sense when comparing country results.

  • I removed Cyprus because it is a very small economy and the calibration for this country is very unstable.
